Headlines.SeoHeadline: The Morning Ledger: JOBS Act Pitfalls
Headlines.Author: David Hall
Headlines.Headline: The Morning Ledger: JOBS Act Pitfalls

PARAGRAPH.#text:
Potential Pitfalls of the JOBS Act. The Senate version of the JOBS Act is expected to sail through the House today and then head to the White House for the president's signature. The bill is designed to loosen regulatory scrutiny on growing companies raising money and complying with securities laws, and has opened a split between the White House, which sponsored it and some Democrats who fear it opens the door to bad behavior. As the Washington Post writes: "Republicans call the measure a 'jobs bill.' Democrats call it an 'IPO' bill, referring to the initial public offerings of stock made by companies to raise money from investors. The White House calls it a 'startup bill,' and its swift progress through Congress reflects Obama's desire to show he has strong business credentials and favors a sensible scaling back of regulations. "
On today's CFO Journal page in the WSJ, Emily Chasan has some startling numbers that highlight the risks of loosening regulations for young companies: Nearly a third of the companies that have gone public since 2004 have come out with financial restatements. It makes sense – as former SEC chief accountant (and JOBS Act critic) Lynn Turner says, an IPO company is typically a smaller company, so it "has fewer resources in the accounting and finance department."
Harvard law professor John Coates tells CFO Magazine that letting companies go public more cost-effectively is a great idea, but he thinks the JOBS Act will end up green-lighting scandalous behavior. "There will just be outright fraud."
Question: Is the JOBS Act a boon for small businesses or a recipe for another Enron? Email us your perspective.

Headlines.Headline: The Morning Ledger: Stimulus Not So Stimulating

PARAGRAPH.#text: Economic stimulus' job record mixed. Companies have received more than $10 billion to create jobs and renewable energy under the American Recovery and Reinvestment Act of 2009, which expired in December, with the Obama Administration urging its revival. While businesses have claimed on federal applications that they created more than 100,000 direct jobs, a Journal investigation found evidence of far fewer, with some plants laying off workers and others closing. The White House estimated that overall stimulus spending created between 2.2 million and 4.2 million jobs as of the second quarter of 2011. But jobs figures reported by grant recipients were full of errors, the Congressional Research Service said in a report last year: "Thus it is recommended that any job creation estimate be viewed with skepticism."

PARAGRAPH.#text: TAKING THE PULSE: The major oil-field-service providers are likely to continue benefiting in the second quarter from the boom in North American drilling and high oil prices around the world. They have been racing to become more efficient as rising demand from energy producers has been stretching them thin. Companies are particularly focused on developing technology to help them more efficiently unlock unconventional reserves, like those locked in shale formations. Deep-water drilling around the world is also an area of strength as drilling resumes in the Gulf of Mexico. However, continuing political unrest in North Africa continues to weigh on the industry's international performance.
